\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted 78966105 1460384364
Neural circuits transform activity and produce activity that is either sent
 to higher brain areas or to muscles to elicit behavior.
 A very simplistic example of this idea is that of the reflex arc, where
 sensory information is relayed to motor neurons in the spinal chord, in
 order to elicit a reflex.
 More complex behaviors, transform the incoming activity to produce a different/
unique output.
 This transformation presumably involves the integration of signals form
 multiple neurons, to produce a suitable output.
 For example a 5 day old larval zebrafish can perform multiple sensory motor
 integrating tasks like tracking of prey and predator avoidance.
 In such behaviors, multiple sensory inputs converge on different brain
 areas, these signals are then transformed to infer motion of prey, or predator
 and elicit a behavior to swim towards or away.
 To understand these transformations, we need to know what the signals are
 (physiology), where they come from (anatomy) and what the transformation
 is (behavior).
