\begin_layout Standard
We studied the population of premotor neurons defined by their encoding
 of eye position.
 This population makes up the neural circuit known as the "velocity-to-position
 neural integrator," or "neural integrator" for short (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Major:2004dk,Joshua:2015kx"

\end_inset

).
 In fish (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Pastor:1994tx,Aksay:2000cn,Aksay:2001fx"

\end_inset

), rodents (), non-human primates (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Robinson:1975vm,Robinson:1989wt"

\end_inset

), and humans (cite), the neural integrator is the "final common pathway"
 for all types of eye movements.
 This neural circuit performs the computational operation of integration
 with respect to time.
 The mechanisms supporting temporal integration remain unclear even after
 decades of research (cite).
 Many hypotheses and models have been proposed, and a number of them invoke
 circuit mechanisms (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kamath_neurological_1976,arnold_oculomotor_1997,seung_continuous_1998,seung_stability_2000,Goldman:2009ko,fisher_modeling_2013"

\end_inset

).

\change_inserted 78966105 1460388748
 Most models assume the existence of recurrent synapses between integrator
 neurons, but this remains to be validated.
\change_unchanged

