\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Synapses ( chemical and possible electrical)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We identified synapses by the presence of a presynaptic vesicle pool and
 an opposing postsynaptic density (fig 2B, EM panels).
 Synapses from or onto integrator neurons contained small vesicles, presumably
 containing a conventional neurotransmitter.
 Elsewhere in the volume we did identify synapses with dense core vesicles,
 presumably containing a peptide neurotransmitter (sup fig).
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We did not label synapses as being either symmetric or asymmetric, to infer
 neurotransmitter identity, as there exists some disagreements regarding
 this method of inference (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Klemann:2011hy"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The postsynaptic densities were observed as a darkening of the membrane,
 indicative of more electron dense regions.
 On the presynaptic side we typically noticed a small pool of vesicles usually
 very close to the postsynaptic density, with a mild darkening of the regions
 close to the synaptic membrane, consistent with the idea of an active-zone,
 where presynaptic machinery that supports the release of vesicles.
 The rest of the axonal terminal contained a larger reserve pool of vesicles
 (fig 2B, EM panels).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
