\begin_layout Standard
Here we reconstructed cells from the hindbrain of the larval zebrafish that
 were involved in converting eye-velocity signals to eye-position signals.
 We functionally imaged from cells in the hindbrain using two-photon microscopy
 during spontaneous eye-movement behavior, followed by serial section electron
 microscopy in the same animal.
 We reconstructed in detail, the anatomy of integrator cells.

\change_inserted 78966105 1460389046
 
\change_unchanged
This analysis, revealed cells with at least three types of unique axonal
 projection patterns.
 We discovered a new type of integrator cell projection pattern, 
\change_inserted 78966105 1460389109
cells with both
\change_unchanged
 
\change_inserted 78966105 1460389115
and 
\change_unchanged
ipsilateral and contralateral projection
\change_inserted 78966105 1460389132
.

\change_unchanged
 Although the contralateral projections were termed 
\change_inserted 78966105 1460389161
'
\change_unchanged
putative
\change_inserted 78966105 1460389163
'
\change_unchanged
, they had all the hallmarks of being axonal in nature.
 The other projection patterns, the ipsilateral and contralateral projections
 have been reported previously in larval zebrafish (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lee:2015dv"

\end_inset

), gold fish (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Pastor:1994tx,Aksay:2000cn"

\end_inset

), cats (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "McCrea:1985hx"

\end_inset

) and nonhuman primates (cite).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The axons of these cells did not begin as axons, in fact they began as dendrites
 and later changed to being axonal.
 This results in the presynaptic sites being farther away from the somata
 as compared to the postsynaptic sites.
 Having more postsynaptic sites close to the somata would mean that a handful
 of postsynaptic sites would be enough to influence the firing of the cell.
 We reported the number of synapses for each of these integrator class,
 and noticed that for the most anatomically compete cells, the ratio of
 inputs to outputs was ~1.6.
 This could possibly be a result of the fact that integrator neurons, apart
 from listening to other integrator neurons, also receive inputs from other
 non integrator neurons, like the saccadic burst neurons.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We inferred the putative neurotransmitter identity of these integrator cells.
 We report that the ipsilaterally projecting cells are putatively glutamatergic,
 the ipsi-contra cell are also glutamatergic, the contralaterally projecting
 cells are GABAergic and the lateral most cells are also glutamatergic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we validated a long standing question in this field, and show that
 integrator cells are synaptically connected.
 We also noticed, that there was connectivity among cells of the same group,
 with the synapses originating from the collaterals of these axons.
 The emergence of axonal collaterals on the same side as other integrator
 cells, suggests the possibility of local feedback loops that might drive
 this persistent activity.
 Supporting this evidence was also evidence that shows that pairs of neurons
 on the same side have highly correlated activity, both in fish (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aksay:2003un"

\end_inset

) and in monkeys (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dale:2015hh"

\end_inset

).
 We also noticed that only one cells made all the synapses with other integrator
 cells.
 This 'super' cell also made the most number of potential synapses onto
 other integrator cells.
 One possibility for the sparse connectivity among ipsilaterally projecting
 cells is because integrator cells from the unilateral population do not
 contribute to the entire oculomotor range.
 We would expect cells that respond to a certain range of eye position to
 synapse onto similar cells, but not with cells from an opposing range of
 eye positions.
 Conversely, these few synapses could be a byproduct of a small number of
 cells with incompletely reconstructed axons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The larval zebrafish is believed to have ~100 integrator neurons unilaterally
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aksay:2003un"

\end_inset

).
 Here we reconstructed 25% of the unilateral integrator circuit.
 
\change_inserted 78966105 1460031140
T
\change_unchanged
he organization of these cells in the larval animal might most likely be
 conserved in the adult (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gilland_hindbrain_2014"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar anatomical approach can be extended further to answer yet more
 question regarding the integrator circuit.
 The contribution of inputs from the same side as compared to the other
 side remain unknown.
 Presumably, this can be answered by tracing all the inputs impinging onto
 an integrator cell, back to their respective cell bodies.
 The integrator circuit is alos active during other eye movement behaviors
 like the optokinetic reflex, the vestebulo-ocular reflex and the optomotor
 response.
 Previous studies using whole brain functional imaging have shown that multiple
 brain areas are involved in these behaviors.
 The anatomical link from there other brain areas to the integrator circuit
 remains to be discovered.
 
\end_layout

